	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have had much the oposite experience with damage and hit/miss ratios.&nbsp;&nbsp;I'm not sure what you're fighting with that bad a record, but at lvl 55, even fighting yellows I hit much more than I miss.  With full Raid buffs I do even better.<br><br>Fighting in XP groups my hits are much closer to 80% of the time.  Using the Dizok Imperial Katana and the Sash of the Dragonborn I usually end up with double 160's with a miss about 1 every 4 rounds (1 miss not a double miss).  When I use the Ebon Mace I'm hitting for double 80's with about the same ratio but alot faster.  <br><br>On Raids with full Shaman/Ranger/Pali buffs I'll hit at least 50% of the time, closer to 60-70% of the time in Temple of Veeshan.<br><br>I have no idea what you are doing to get such a high miss rate.  I would suggest you try getting closer to the MOB, changing your relative position often will help you hit more.  Besides that I'd say you were just having a string of bad luck when you did your numbers.<br><br>While this discipline is not over-powering, I have seen it used to great effect by other SK's in my Guild.  It is often used when they take up the roll of Main Tank for unexpected reasons during Raids (like the extra un-mezzable add).  With this discipline I have seen a lvl 60 DE SK survive many an encounter as Main Tank after the Secondary Tank Warrior died trying to tank the same add.  The strength of this discipline as I've seen it is to let the SK get 15 seconds of agro time without needing any healing, and get the Cleric's attention that he'll be needing heals before he drops too low on health.  When needed this dicipline should hold your health steady against all but the hardest hitting opponent giving the Clerics time to start the healing cycle on you.<br><br>It's not worthless, in fact I'm looking forward to it.  But it does require good buffs, good gear and some luck.<br><br><br>Neptunis Rex<br>lvl 55 DE Revenant<br>&nbsp;<br>Neptunis Rex<